body:
I encountered this error when accidentally duplicating an import from inside a glob.

```rust
mod foo {
    pub mod bar {
        pub mod bar {}
    }
}

use foo::*;
use bar::bar;
use bar::bar;
```

I had expected this would error due to blantly defining the same name twice but instead it says something about name resolution failing.

```
error: cannot determine resolution for the import
  --> src/lib.rs:10:5
   |
10 | use bar::bar;
   |     ^^^^^^^^
   |
   = note: import resolution is stuck, try simplifying other imports

error: cannot determine resolution for the import
  --> src/lib.rs:11:5
   |
11 | use bar::bar;
   |     ^^^^^^^^
   |
   = note: import resolution is stuck, try simplifying other imports

error[E0432]: unresolved imports `bar::bar`, `bar::bar`
  --> src/lib.rs:10:5
   |
10 | use bar::bar;
   |     ^^^^^^^^
11 | use bar::bar;
   |     ^^^^^^^^
```

The same example without the glob and defining the module directly results in the expected error message:

```rust
pub mod foo {
    pub mod bar {
        pub mod bar {}
    }
}

use foo::bar;
use bar::bar;
use bar::bar;
```

<details>
<summary>Expected error trace to error[E0252]: the name `bar` is defined multiple times</summary>
<pre>
error[E0255]: the name `bar` is defined multiple times
 --> src/lib.rs:7:5
  |
2 |     pub mod bar {
  |     ----------- previous definition of the module `bar` here
...
7 | use bar::bar;
  |     ^^^^^^^^ `bar` reimported here
  |
  = note: `bar` must be defined only once in the type namespace of this module
help: you can use `as` to change the binding name of the import
  |
7 | use bar::bar as other_bar;
  |     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

error[E0255]: the name `bar` is defined multiple times
 --> src/lib.rs:8:5
  |
2 |     pub mod bar {
  |     ----------- previous definition of the module `bar` here
...
8 | use bar::bar;
  |     ^^^^^^^^ `bar` reimported here
  |
  = note: `bar` must be defined only once in the type namespace of this module
help: you can use `as` to change the binding name of the import

</pre>
</details>
